And also, it's per-- it's
personal, it's political

00:51:05.110 --> 00:51:10.390
and my family is just filled
with -- with strife and--

00:51:10.390 --> 00:51:14.820
yeah, and therefore
I feel like I must--

00:51:14.820 --> 00:51:17.420
I must write about-- about it.

00:51:17.420 --> 00:51:18.720
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: What's
so chilling is, you know,

00:51:18.720 --> 00:51:21.070
each of those, are
they quatrain?

00:51:21.070 --> 00:51:22.690
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin:
They're octaves, yeah.

00:51:22.690 --> 00:51:23.990
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Octaves.

00:51:23.990 --> 00:51:25.960
Each of them is parallel,
each of them very similar,

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:27.290
but each of them different,
in different cultures

00:51:27.290 --> 00:51:28.910
at different times, obviously,

00:51:28.910 --> 00:51:31.890
but it's essentially the same
story over and over again.

00:51:31.890 --> 00:51:33.190
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Right.

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:34.490
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It
reminds me, of course,

00:51:34.490 --> 00:51:36.360
of Dr. Ford's testimony when
women all over the country said,

00:51:36.360 --> 00:51:39.570
yes, that's exactly-- even
people in my own family told me,

00:51:39.570 --> 00:51:41.790
yes, that's exactly what
happened to me at a party.

00:51:41.790 --> 00:51:43.090
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Yes.

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:44.390
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Everyone's
had this happen apparently.

00:51:44.390 --> 00:51:47.070
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Yes, and--
and women's issue-- I mean--

00:51:47.070 --> 00:51:51.960
I mean I wrote this poem, what
20 years ago and it's, you know,

00:51:51.960 --> 00:51:53.870
and the theme-- it's universal.

00:51:53.870 --> 00:51:55.170
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes.

00:51:55.170 --> 00:51:56.690
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: We're still
suffering from, you know,

00:51:56.690 --> 00:51:59.030
from domestic vi--
from violence.

00:51:59.030 --> 00:52:00.450
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: And
the denial of it.

00:52:00.450 --> 00:52:01.750
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin:
And denial, yes.

00:52:01.750 --> 00:52:03.050
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: That's
all part of it.

00:52:03.050 --> 00:52:05.840
It's acting like it never
happens or being surprised.

00:52:05.840 --> 00:52:08.010
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin:
And-- and, yeah.

00:52:08.010 --> 00:52:11.420
So, yeah, that's--
that's why these--

00:52:11.420 --> 00:52:13.750
you know, certain poems live on.

00:52:13.750 --> 00:52:18.040
You know, they're-- they're
un-- they're universal.

00:52:18.040 --> 00:52:20.660
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Every
Woman Is Her Own Chimera.

00:52:20.660 --> 00:52:23.990
That's a very different kind
of feminist poem, right.

00:52:23.990 --> 00:52:27.700
Where is that?

00:52:27.700 --> 00:52:30.550
Number 16.

00:52:30.550 --> 00:52:33.620
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: I wrote
this poem for Adrienne Rich.

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:35.420
Did you know Adrienne Rich?

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:36.720
Yeah.

00:52:36.720 --> 00:52:38.020
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I-- I
can't have you read the--

00:52:38.020 --> 00:52:39.320
we won't get through
the whole thing

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:41.510
but just you'll see
when to stop.

00:52:41.510 --> 00:52:42.810
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: You
want-- should I read this?

00:52:42.810 --> 00:52:44.110
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: I've
got a little mark

00:52:44.110 --> 00:52:47.300
on the other side, next page.

00:52:47.300 --> 00:52:48.600
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin:
I-- I stop here?

00:52:48.600 --> 00:52:49.900
I read--

00:52:49.900 --> 00:52:51.200
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes please.

00:52:51.200 --> 00:52:52.500
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Okay.

00:52:52.500 --> 00:52:53.800
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Thank you.

00:52:53.800 --> 00:52:55.100
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Yeah, I wrote
this suite for Adrienne Rich.

00:52:55.100 --> 00:52:56.900
Every Woman is Her Own Chimera.

00:52:56.900 --> 00:52:59.290
Every woman is her own chimera.

00:52:59.290 --> 00:53:02.010
Today she is laughing
with Julio.

00:53:02.010 --> 00:53:05.620
Tonight, she is dancing
with Coolio.

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:08.710
How long can happiness last?

00:53:08.710 --> 00:53:12.840
For a slow brief afternoon,
my head on the thigh

00:53:12.840 --> 00:53:17.170
of a Sequoia, reading Wang Wei.

00:53:17.170 --> 00:53:21.070
Butterfly in mouth,
but don't bite down.

00:53:21.070 --> 00:53:23.230
Whose life is it anyway?

00:53:23.230 --> 00:53:30.720
She born of chrysalis and shit
or she born of woman and pain?

00:53:30.720 --> 00:53:34.160
Mei Ling brings a
wounded poem, cry--

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:37.480
crying, please, mommy,
mommy fix it.

00:53:37.480 --> 00:53:40.000
You wipe the tears
from her cheek,

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:44.090
then glue a gnat's torn wing.

00:53:44.090 --> 00:53:46.770
The sand dab flicks her tail.

00:53:46.770 --> 00:53:50.250
The tears of the
wombat are green.

00:53:50.250 --> 00:53:54.730
Kiss me against the
last hydrangea.

00:53:54.730 --> 00:53:58.350
Comrades, we are not yet free.

00:53:59.510 --> 00:54:02.810
[ Applause ]

00:54:02.810 --> 00:54:04.110
Yeah.

00:54:04.110 --> 00:54:05.420
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Women aren't
just victims in your poems.

00:54:05.420 --> 00:54:06.780
They push back.

00:54:06.780 --> 00:54:08.950
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Oh yeah, they
talk back, they push back.

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:10.250
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: They fight back.

00:54:10.250 --> 00:54:11.550
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin:
They fight back.

00:54:11.550 --> 00:54:14.930
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: They-- what
they say about a woman at 45;

00:54:14.930 --> 00:54:18.060
too late to live, too
soon to die [laughter].

00:54:18.060 --> 00:54:22.000
My wine is bittersweet,
my song is rye.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:24.080
You go on to talk about
other parts of your body,

00:54:24.080 --> 00:54:25.880
which I will not read.

00:54:25.880 --> 00:54:29.050
[ Laughter ]

00:54:29.050 --> 00:54:33.510
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Yeah,
he's afraid of the c word

00:54:33.510 --> 00:54:38.160
and the v word he's
afraid of [laughter].

00:54:38.160 --> 00:54:39.780
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: But
it is very funny.

00:54:39.780 --> 00:54:42.120
It's a very funny poem.

00:54:42.120 --> 00:54:45.570
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: There's a v
word, okay, and a c word, okay.

00:54:45.570 --> 00:54:46.870
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: In the afterward

00:54:46.870 --> 00:54:49.850
to the Phoenix Gone you write
I have not been rehabilitated

00:54:49.850 --> 00:54:51.150
in middle age.

00:54:51.150 --> 00:54:53.470
In fact, I want to reassure
my friends that I am as feisty

00:54:53.470 --> 00:54:54.770
as ever, which we've
clearly seen.

00:54:54.770 --> 00:54:58.270
I am still very much an activist
poet who believes in my work,

00:54:58.270 --> 00:55:01.260
my life work, to infuse my art
with three powers; to inspire,

00:55:01.260 --> 00:55:03.370
to illuminate, and to liberate.

00:55:03.370 --> 00:55:06.180
How does poetry do those things?

00:55:06.180 --> 00:55:08.810
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin:
Oh, as Oden says,

00:55:08.810 --> 00:55:13.060
poetry makes nothing
happen, right [laughter].

00:55:13.060 --> 00:55:17.990
Well it's-- it's important
that the poet believes that,

00:55:17.990 --> 00:55:19.370
you know, she can
do these things.

00:55:19.370 --> 00:55:20.670
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes.

00:55:20.670 --> 00:55:21.970
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: It's
important for the poet to--

00:55:21.970 --> 00:55:25.950
to have this grand scheme
of-- you know, of things.

00:55:25.950 --> 00:55:28.860
I don't know.

00:55:28.860 --> 00:55:34.180
This is-- this-- I just retired
from my full-time teaching job.

00:55:34.180 --> 00:55:37.270
I'm going to, you know, run
around the country and talk

00:55:37.270 --> 00:55:40.670
about poetry and-- and
bring the good news,

00:55:40.670 --> 00:55:43.880
present the good news, and
it's-- it's important, I think.

00:55:43.880 --> 00:55:46.270
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Your poems do
that, but they also push back

00:55:46.270 --> 00:55:51.030
at our temptation to speak in
a grandiose way about poetry.

00:55:51.030 --> 00:55:52.330
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Right, right.

00:55:52.330 --> 00:55:53.630
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Several
witty lines here.

00:55:53.630 --> 00:55:56.590
The poet guards the
conscious of society.

00:55:56.590 --> 00:55:57.890
No, you're wrong [laughter].

00:55:57.890 --> 00:56:02.800
She stands lonely on that hill
like observing the pastures.

00:56:02.800 --> 00:56:05.520
Later you say, I do hate my
loneliness, sitting cross-legged

00:56:05.520 --> 00:56:07.920
in my room, satisfied
with a few off rhymes,

00:56:07.920 --> 00:56:09.220
sending off precious haiku

00:56:09.220 --> 00:56:11.950
to some inconspicuous
journal named Lev Leaning

00:56:11.950 --> 00:56:14.340
Bamboo [laughter].

00:56:14.340 --> 00:56:17.210
It's such a great
satire of the poet.

00:56:17.210 --> 00:56:22.760
And finally, how could we write
poetry in a time like this,

00:56:22.760 --> 00:56:26.440
a discipline that makes so
much ado about so little.

00:56:26.440 --> 00:56:29.660
Willfully laconic, deceptively
disguised as a love poem.

00:56:29.660 --> 00:56:32.670
I mean you implicitly
challenge poetry,

00:56:32.670 --> 00:56:34.500
not to claim more
than it can do.

00:56:34.500 --> 00:56:35.800
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Right, right.

00:56:35.800 --> 00:56:39.290
And-- well I-- but I
still love the genre.

00:56:39.290 --> 00:56:40.590
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Oh yes.

00:56:40.590 --> 00:56:42.250
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: You know,
it's the genre that's closest

00:56:42.250 --> 00:56:44.840
to our hearts, when
you're sad and lonely

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:47.840
and angry you write a
little poem, you know,

00:56:47.840 --> 00:56:49.160
you write poems, you know.

00:56:49.160 --> 00:56:50.880
And so, yeah, yeah.

00:56:50.880 --> 00:56:56.070
I just-- well, you know, a
poet, we're-- we're the--

00:56:56.070 --> 00:56:58.540
we're the step-children
of literature, aren't we?

00:56:58.540 --> 00:56:59.840
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: No.

00:56:59.840 --> 00:57:02.510
No. You're the queens and kings.

00:57:02.510 --> 00:57:05.360
[ Laughter ]

00:57:05.360 --> 00:57:07.510
Look at you laughing.

00:57:07.510 --> 00:57:12.430
[ Laughter ]

00:57:12.430 --> 00:57:17.320
There's a wonderful tribute poem
here I want you to read the--

00:57:17.320 --> 00:57:23.780
the first part, and
this will be the end.

00:57:23.780 --> 00:57:25.140
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: I read here?

00:57:25.140 --> 00:57:26.440
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Yes.

00:57:26.440 --> 00:57:27.740
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Okay.

00:57:27.740 --> 00:57:29.130
This-- I wrote this
for my friend,

00:57:29.130 --> 00:57:31.870
the activist poet,
Mitsuye Yamada.

00:57:31.870 --> 00:57:36.240
Do you-- any of-- yeah, I wrote
it for her 90th birthday and--

00:57:36.240 --> 00:57:37.540
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: She's
still alive.

00:57:37.540 --> 00:57:38.920
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: She's
still alive, she's 93,

00:57:38.920 --> 00:57:43.030
and she calls me and says
when are you going to come

00:57:43.030 --> 00:57:45.290
and visit me, I might
not have long, you know,

00:57:45.290 --> 00:57:46.590
I might have another year.

00:57:46.590 --> 00:57:48.510
And so, it's-- she's
really great.

00:57:48.510 --> 00:57:51.190
But she's-- she was
one of the fir--

00:57:51.190 --> 00:57:54.540
you know, first Asian-American
poets that I read and her--

00:57:54.540 --> 00:58:01.200
and her father was
inturned, you know, she was--

00:58:01.200 --> 00:58:05.130
you know, was taken away
to an internment camp.

00:58:05.130 --> 00:58:08.130
For Mitsuye Yamada
on her 90th birthday.

00:58:08.130 --> 00:58:11.460
They say we bitch
revolutionaries never go

00:58:11.460 --> 00:58:13.690
out of fashion.

00:58:13.690 --> 00:58:16.180
Look how fashionable
I am [laughter].

00:58:16.180 --> 00:58:20.250
Wearing floppy hats
and huge wedgy shoes.

00:58:20.250 --> 00:58:24.230
A feather bandolera
and a lethal python.

00:58:24.230 --> 00:58:29.210
Sometimes we wear a fro perm
cause we hate our straight hair.

00:58:29.210 --> 00:58:34.070
Sometimes we wear it straight
to the ankles like Murasaki.

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:39.290
I bleached mine purple to
look like Kwannon Psylocke.

00:58:39.290 --> 00:58:42.470
Maxine's beaming, like the
Goddess of Nainai temple.

00:58:42.470 --> 00:58:47.530
A cross between Storm, the
X-girl and Ahsoka Tano.

00:58:47.530 --> 00:58:52.420
We love our laser eyes; our
Yoko granny glasses are dizzy.

00:58:52.420 --> 00:58:55.400
Short women poets unite!

00:58:55.400 --> 00:58:59.510
Revolution ain't just
style, it's destiny!

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:07.040
[ Laughter and Applause ]

00:59:07.040 --> 00:59:09.080
Remember those spiral perms?

00:59:09.080 --> 00:59:11.490
I don't know, you
guys are too young.

00:59:11.490 --> 00:59:14.950
Oh, the spiral perms
in the 80s, you know.

00:59:14.950 --> 00:59:17.800
I had-- ugh, yeah.

00:59:17.800 --> 00:59:20.570
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: It's been such a
pleasure to talk to you tonight.

00:59:20.570 --> 00:59:21.870
Thank you so much.

00:59:21.870 --> 00:59:23.170
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Oh, thank you.

00:59:23.170 --> 00:59:24.470
It's-- the hour's over.

00:59:24.470 --> 00:59:25.770
I can't believe it.

00:59:25.770 --> 00:59:27.070
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: There
are poem books--

00:59:27.070 --> 00:59:28.370
there are collections
for sale in the lobby.

00:59:28.370 --> 00:59:30.200
Please fill out the
questionnaires and feel free

00:59:30.200 --> 00:59:31.500
to come up and talk to Marilyn.

00:59:31.500 --> 00:59:32.800
&gt;&gt; Marilyn Chin: Oh,
thank you so much.

00:59:32.800 --> 00:59:34.100
Thank you [applause].

00:59:34.100 --> 00:59:35.400
Thank you for coming.

00:59:35.400 --> 00:59:36.700
Thank you.

00:59:36.700 --> 00:59:38.000
Thank you.

